# This issue is generated by Claude. But I tried this mitigation myself and it's working so I'm here to share it. I have ABSOLUTELY no knowledge developing games and Csharp. I'm sorry.

When entering the Song Select screen, the game experiences severe frame drops, often dropping from 900+ FPS to below 400 FPS. The root cause is a burst of GPU texture uploads triggered by glyph cache misses when beatmap panel text (titles, artists, difficulty names) is rendered for the first time.

## Environment

- Platform: Linux, AMD Radeon, Vulkan (Deferred renderer)
- Beatmap count: ~500+ sets with multilingual metadata (CJK)

## Root Cause Analysis

The frame drop is caused by a chain of events:

### 1. Glyph miss → Atlas upload → Queue spike

When `SpriteText` renders a character it hasn't seen before, `FontStore.Get()` is called.
On a cache miss, the glyph bitmap is fetched from the `GlyphStore`, packed into a
`TextureAtlas` slice, and enqueued for GPU upload via `VeldridTexture.SetData()`.

Each glyph slice is split into up to 9 sub-region uploads due to atlas padding handling
in `TextureAtlas_BackingAtlasTexture`. So 100 glyph misses → ~900 entries in the upload
queue.

```csharp
// osu-framework: VeldridTexture.cs
public void SetData(ITextureUpload upload)
{
    lock (uploadQueue)
    {
        // logs "upload queue is large (N)" every 100 items
        bool requireUpload = uploadQueue.Count == 0;
        uploadQueue.Enqueue(upload);

        if (requireUpload && !BypassTextureUploadQueueing)
            Renderer.EnqueueTextureUpload(this); // only enqueues the texture object once
    }
}
```

### 2. `Upload()` drains the entire queue in one frame

When the renderer processes a texture object, `Upload()` calls `tryGetNextUpload()` in
an unbounded `while` loop — all pending sub-region uploads for that atlas are flushed in
a single frame:

```csharp
// osu-framework: VeldridTexture.cs — current behaviour
public bool Upload()
{
    // ...
    while (tryGetNextUpload(out ITextureUpload? upload))  // NO limit!
    {
        using (upload)
            DoUpload(upload); // synchronous GPU upload on the draw thread
    }
    // ...
}
```

With 400–1500 pending sub-region uploads, this stalls the draw thread for tens of
milliseconds.

### 3. `Renderer.cs` throttle is ineffective

`Renderer.cs` limits the number of *texture objects* dequeued per frame, but since each
texture object drains all its pending sub-uploads in one call, the limit provides no real
protection against a burst:

```csharp
// osu-framework: Renderer.cs
int targetUploads = Math.Clamp(textureUploadQueue.Count / 2, 1, MaxTexturesUploadedPerFrame);

while (textureUploadQueue.TryDequeue(out INativeTexture? texture))
{
    if (!texture.Upload())  // this can flush hundreds of sub-uploads in one call
        continue;
    if (++uploads >= targetUploads) break;
}
```

### 4. Song Select panels trigger the burst synchronously on the UI thread

`BeatmapCarousel.updateDisplayedRange()` adds all newly visible panels in one pass.
Each panel's `PrepareForUse()` sets `titleText.Text` and `artistText.Text`, which
immediately triggers `SpriteText`'s glyph lookup for every character in the beatmap
title/artist — including CJK, Cyrillic, Japanese kana, etc. All of these are cold-cache
misses on first load.

```csharp
// osu: PanelBeatmapSet.cs
protected override void PrepareForUse()
{
    // Both lines trigger synchronous glyph lookups for every character:
    titleText.Text  = new RomanisableString(beatmapSet.Metadata.TitleUnicode, beatmapSet.Metadata.Title);
    artistText.Text = new RomanisableString(beatmapSet.Metadata.ArtistUnicode, beatmapSet.Metadata.Artist);
}
```

### Confirmed via log evidence

The following lines appear in a burst within the same timestamp second as Song Select
entry, confirming the upload queue explosion:

```
[runtime]     Texture -'s upload queue is large (100)
[runtime]     Texture -'s upload queue is large (200)
[runtime]     Texture -'s upload queue is large (300)
[runtime]     Texture -'s upload queue is large (400)
[performance] TextureAtlas size exceeded 3 time(s); generating new texture (1024x1024)
```

Disabling panel text (replacing titles/artists with blank strings) eliminated the frame
drop entirely, confirming glyph uploads as the sole cause.

## Proposed Fix

The most effective mitigation found during investigation: **pre-warm glyph lookups across
multiple frames during the intro/loading period**, before the user reaches Song Select.

This requires a small addition to `FontStore` in osu-framework to expose font load
completion:

```csharp
// osu-framework: FontStore.cs
private Task childStoreLoadTasks;

/// <summary>Returns a task that completes once all queued font loads have finished.</summary>
public Task WhenAllFontsLoaded() => childStoreLoadTasks ?? Task.CompletedTask;
```

Then in osu, schedule per-frame glyph pre-warming after fonts are ready:

```csharp
// osu: OsuGameBase.cs
protected override void LoadComplete()
{
    base.LoadComplete();

    // After all fonts finish loading, spread glyph pre-warming across frames
    // so the atlas is populated before Song Select is opened.
    Fonts.WhenAllFontsLoaded().ContinueWith(_ => Scheduler.AddOnce(scheduleGlyphWarmup));
}

private void scheduleGlyphWarmup()
{
    const string ascii = " !\"#$%&'()*+,-./0123456789:;<=>?"
                       + "@ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ[\\]^_`"
                       + "abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz{|}~";

    string[] families =
    {
        "Torus-Regular",          "Torus-SemiBold",          "Torus-Bold",
        "Torus-Alternate-Regular","Torus-Alternate-SemiBold", "Torus-Alternate-Bold",
        "Inter-Regular",          "Inter-SemiBold",           "Inter-Bold",
        "Venera-Bold",
    };

    var lookups = new Queue<(string family, char c)>();

    foreach (string family in families)
        foreach (char c in ascii)
            lookups.Enqueue((family, c));

    // FontAwesome icons commonly used throughout the UI.
    char[] faIcons =
    {
        '\uF002', '\uF004', '\uF00D', '\uF028', '\uF03E', '\uF04B',
        '\uF053', '\uF054', '\uF057', '\uF071', '\uF077', '\uF078',
        '\uF0C0', '\uF0C9', '\uF0E0', '\uF144', '\uF1CE', '\uF502',
    };

    foreach (char icon in faIcons)
    {
        lookups.Enqueue(("FontAwesome-Solid", icon));
        lookups.Enqueue(("FontAwesome-Regular", icon));
    }

    // Also pre-warm characters seen in previous sessions (CJK beatmap titles etc.)
    // loaded from a small persistent cache file written on exit.
    foreach (char c in loadPanelCharCache())
        lookups.Enqueue((null!, c));

    // 20 glyphs per frame keeps the upload queue well below the warning threshold.
    const int batchSize = 20;

    void processBatch()
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < batchSize && lookups.Count > 0; i++)
        {
            var (family, c) = lookups.Dequeue();
            Fonts.Get(family, c);
        }

        if (lookups.Count > 0)
            Scheduler.AddOnce(processBatch);
    }

    Scheduler.AddOnce(processBatch);
}
```

**Result:** Frame drops on Song Select entry are eliminated on warm sessions. A
persistent character cache (written on exit, seeded from the realm database on first
launch) extends the benefit to multilingual titles on first run.

## Additional Notes

- A deeper fix in `VeldridTexture.Upload()` (capping sub-region uploads per frame and
  re-enqueuing the texture for the remainder) was explored but requires careful handling
  of partial-upload state to avoid visual artifacts:

  ```csharp
  // osu-framework: VeldridTexture.cs — sketch of per-frame upload limit
  private const int max_uploads_per_frame = 64;

  public bool Upload()
  {
      // ...
      int processed = 0;

      while (tryGetNextUpload(out ITextureUpload? upload))
      {
          using (upload)
              DoUpload(upload);

          if (++processed >= max_uploads_per_frame)
          {
              // Re-enqueue so the remainder is processed next frame.
              Renderer.EnqueueTextureUpload(this);
              break;
          }
      }
      // ...
  }
  ```

In osu!'s tournament overlay's `TournamentBeatmapPanel`, the flashing behaviour is essentially implemented using a box inside a container with a border like so:
```cs
            Box flash = null!;

            AddStep("add container", () =>
            {
                Add(new Container
                {
                    Masking = true,
                    RelativeSizeAxes = Axes.Both,
                    BorderThickness = 32,
                    BorderColour = Color4Extensions.FromHex("#AA1414"),
                    Children = new Drawable[]
                    {
                        new Box { RelativeSizeAxes = Axes.Both, Colour = Color4.DarkBlue },
                        flash = new Box
                        {
                            RelativeSizeAxes = Axes.Both,
                            Colour = Color4.Gray,
                            Blending = BlendingParameters.Additive,
                            Alpha = 0
                        }
                    }
                });
            });

            AddStep("trigger normal flash", () =>
            {
                flash.Colour = Color4.Gray;
                flash.FadeOutFromOne(500);
            });

            AddStep("trigger black flash", () =>
            {
                flash.Colour = Color4.Black;
                flash.FadeOutFromOne(500);
            });
```
When the box's alpha isn't 0, the container's border color brightens quite significantly (even if the box's color is set to black while using additive blending, see video).

If `Blending` is set to `Mixture` instead of `Additive`, the lightening of the border doesn't happen anymore.

https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9725a8aa-0fb6-4346-ad76-059df830abd2

@frenzibyte suggested adding `AlwaysPresent = true` to the flash box, which does remove the momentary lightening of the border. However, it permanently changes the border's colour (set to `#AA1414` in code, displays as `#FF2828`)

Through [this issue](https://github.com/ppy/osu-framework/issues/6576), we already know that when `SDL3Window` initializes, it reads the `SDL_HINT_ORIENTATIONS` instead of `RequestedOrientation`, which can cause problems.

So, a possible solution is to use `SDL.SDL3.SDL_SetHint` to pre-assign the orientation we need.

However, this still doesn't avoid another problem: besides during initialization, the `Window.Resizable` property will call this [`setOrientationBis`](https://github.com/libsdl-org/SDL/blob/d16371b923fed57e5df676a84435baf1d1061a6a/android-project/app/src/main/java/org/libsdl/app/SDLActivity.java#L1125) method again when its value changes. And I think users might not expect this. For example:

- A user might initially, similar to osu!, not assign a hint and use `RequestedOrientation` to set the screen orientation to a specific value. Then, some method (perhaps a cross-platform settings option) tries to change the value of `Resizable`: `Window.Resizable = !Window.Resizable`. Then, `RequestedOrientation` will suddenly be changed to `FullUser`. And what's stranger is that executing `Window.Resizable = !Window.Resizable` again will not restore the screen orientation, but will fix the screen to landscape or portrait.
  ```cs
  class MyGame : Game {
    [Reslove]
    AndroidGameActivity activity;
    [BackgroundDependencyLoader]
    load() => this.activity.RequestedOrientation = ScreenOrientation.Landscape;

    // By this action, RequestedOrientation may become `FullUser`, or `SensorLandscape`, or `SensorLandscape`
    override OnClick() => Window.Resizable = !Window.Resizable;
  }
  ```
- Alternatively, a user might use a hint to make the screen display in landscape for things like loading screens. Then, there's an in-game setting to force the program into portrait mode. At this point, `RequestedOrientation` must be used, as `SDL_HINT_ORIENTATIONS` does not notify Android that its status has changed. Then, if an attempt is made to change the `Resizable` value while in portrait mode, the `SDL_HINT_ORIENTATIONS` takes effect again, forcing the screen back to landscape. And changing `Resizable` back to its original value has no effect. I believe users who haven't seen any comments about this would be very confused.
  ```cs
  class AndroidGameActivity {
    override OnCreate() => SDL.SDL3.SDL_SetHint(SDL.SDL3.SDL_HINT_ORIENTATIONS, "LandscapeRight"u8);
  }
  class MyGame : Game {
    [Reslove]
    AndroidGameActivity activity;
    [BackgroundDependencyLoader]
    load() => this.activity.RequestedOrientation = ScreenOrientation.Landscape;

    // By this action, RequestedOrientation will become `ReverseLandscape`
    override OnClick() => Window.Resizable = !Window.Resizable;
  }
  ```

Here's [a sample program](https://github.com/Frederisk/osu-framework/tree/ScreenOrientation-Example). Just install the compiled `SampleGame.Android` project on your device. You can try clicking some buttons and observe how the screen orientation changes.

So, do we also need additional wiki documentation or comments for `Resizable` to inform users about this unusual issue? For example, mentioning that changing `Resizable` in Android can cause unexpected orientation changes, or reminding users to record the value of `RequestedOrientation` before modifying `Resizable` in Android and restore it after the call is complete.

By the way, I have a potentially viable solution for the three related issues, which is to override the `SetOrientationBis` method in `AndroidGameActivity`. I have already checked the complete call chain. But after asking for others' opinions on Discord, I received the reply, "If it works, then don't touch it." So, whether to solve these problems, or to consider them not to be problems, is entirely up to you guys. I have no other ideas.😕
